    specs: [],
    alternatives: [
      { name: 'Best Standing Desk for Home Office', href: '/reviews/best-standing-desk-home-office/', desc: 'Detailed review of the Branch Standing Desk for home office use.' },
      { name: 'Best Standing Desk Under $300', href: '/reviews/best-standing-desk-under-300/', desc: 'Budget standing desk roundup led by the FlexiSpot E7.' },
      { name: 'FlexiSpot vs Uplift Standing Desk', href: '/compare/flexispot-vs-uplift-standing-desk/', desc: 'Brand-level comparison of the two most popular standing desk brands.' },
    ],
    faqs: [
      { question: 'What is the best standing desk in 2026?', answer: 'The best standing desk depends on your budget. The Uplift V2 ($599) is the best overall for its unmatched stability, 335 lb capacity, and 15-year warranty. The FlexiSpot E7 ($249) is the best value, delivering 85% of the Uplift V2\'s performance at 42% of the price. The Vari Electric ($395) is the best mid-range pick with included cable management and easy assembly. For most home office users, the FlexiSpot E7 is the best starting point.' },
      { question: 'Are standing desks worth it?', answer: 'Yes, if you use the sit-stand feature regularly. Studies show alternating between sitting and standing every 30-60 minutes reduces back pain and improves energy. A good standing desk lasts 10+ years, making it a solid health investment. However, if you only stand occasionally, a desk converter ($100-200) is a cheaper alternative that delivers most of the health benefits.' },
      { question: 'How much should I spend on a standing desk?', answer: 'Spend at least $250 for a stable desk with a dual motor. Under $200, you will get noticeable wobble at full height and louder motors. The sweet spot for quality and value is $250-600. The FlexiSpot E7 at $249 is the best value pick, while the Uplift V2 at $599 is the best premium option. Spending more than $600 only makes sense if you want specific top finishes or a larger size.' },
      { question: 'Do standing desks help with back pain?', answer: 'Yes, when used correctly. Alternating between sitting and standing every 30-60 minutes reduces pressure on the lower back and engages core muscles. However, standing all day is just as bad as sitting all day. The key is movement — use a sit-stand desk to change positions regularly, and take short walks every hour. According to ergonomic studies, users who alternate positions report 30% less back pain than those who sit all day.' },
      { question: 'What weight capacity do I need in a standing desk?', answer: 'For a single monitor setup with a laptop, 150 lbs is sufficient. For a dual-monitor setup with a desktop PC, look for 220 lbs or higher. For heavy ultrawide monitors (35+ lbs) or multi-monitor arrays, choose a desk with 300+ lbs capacity like the Uplift V2. Insufficient weight capacity leads to wobble at maximum height, which is both annoying and potentially unsafe for expensive equipment.' },
    ],
