    faqs: [
      { question: 'What is the best mechanical keyboard in 2026?', answer: 'The best mechanical keyboard depends on your budget and use case. The Keychron Q1 ($179) is the best overall for its CNC aluminum frame, gasket mount, and QMK/VIA customization. The Keychron K8 ($84) is the best value, delivering Bluetooth 5.1, hot-swappable switches, and a 78-hour battery. The Logitech MX Keys S ($119) is the best for office productivity with smart backlighting and multi-device pairing. For most first-time buyers, the Keychron K8 is the best starting point.' },
      { question: 'Are mechanical keyboards worth it?', answer: 'Yes, if you type for more than 2 hours per day. Mechanical keyboards offer better typing feel, durability, and customization than membrane keyboards. The tactile feedback reduces typing errors, and the hot-swappable switches on models like the Keychron K8 and Q1 extend the keyboard\'s lifespan indefinitely. A good mechanical keyboard lasts 5-10 years, making the cost per year comparable to cheaper membrane keyboards that need replacement every 1-2 years.' },
      { question: 'What switches are best for office use?', answer: 'Tactile switches like Gateron Brown or Cherry MX Brown are best for office use. They provide a tactile bump for typing feedback without the loud click of blue switches, making them office-appropriate at around 50 dB. Linear switches like Cherry MX Red are quieter but lack feedback, making typing errors more common. If you work in a shared office, avoid clicky switches (Cherry MX Blue, Razer Green) — they exceed 60 dB and annoy coworkers.' },
      { question: 'What is a hot-swappable mechanical keyboard?', answer: 'A hot-swappable keyboard allows you to change the switches without soldering. The switches plug into sockets on the circuit board and can be pulled out with a switch puller and replaced in seconds. This feature, found on the Keychron K8 and Q1, extends the keyboard\'s lifespan indefinitely — if a switch fails, you replace it for about $1 instead of buying a new keyboard. Hot-swap also lets you try different switch types without buying multiple keyboards.' },
      { question: 'Should I get a TKL or 60% mechanical keyboard?', answer: 'It depends on your workflow. A TKL (tenkeyless) keyboard removes the numpad but keeps the arrow keys and function row, making it the best all-around choice for most users. A 60% keyboard removes the arrow keys and function row, relying on layer shortcuts for those keys — this saves desk space but requires learning a new key layout. If you use arrow keys frequently for editing or navigation, choose TKL. If you want maximum desk space and are willing to learn layer shortcuts, 60% is a compact alternative.' },
    ],
